<BaseLayout title="Methodology" description="How UK Elections will collect, label, model, and backtest election data.">
  <section class="page-hero">
    <p class="eyebrow">Methodology</p>
    <h1>Separate facts, features, and forecasts.</h1>
    <p class="lede">
      The site treats official records as source data, derived indicators as features, and
      predictions as model outputs. Each layer has its own provenance and review rules.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="section prose-block">
    <h2>Publication rules</h2>
    <p>Candidate and result facts must link to a primary or named secondary source. Model features must describe their source data and transformation. Forecast outputs must include uncertainty, a timestamp, and the model version that produced them.</p>

    <h2>Model families</h2>
    <p>Borough, county, unitary, Westminster, Senedd, and Scottish Parliament contests need separate model families. A borough election is ward-first and candidate-first; a county election is division-first; Senedd and Scottish Parliament elections need allocation models that match their voting systems.</p>

    <h2>Local election gate</h2>
    <p>No local forecast should publish until the ward or division boundary, wards up, defending councillor, candidate roster, local result history, and demographic joins have passed source review. County results can inform a borough model, but they cannot replace borough ward evidence.</p>

    <h2>Internal pilots</h2>
    <p>The AI DOGE Burnley and Lancashire work is a useful internal pilot because it has refined ward-level election history, candidate handling, and UKD demographic features. It still needs source review, licensing checks, and borough-specific validation before any output is treated as public forecast data.</p>

    <h2>Backtesting</h2>
    <p>Backtests are part of the product, not an internal notebook. The public record should show calibration, error distribution, biggest misses, and whether model changes improve the archived result.</p>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
